Incident.Summary: The front seat passenger of the vehicle was in possession of marijuana, personal use.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
This incident was captured on in-car/body-worn camera. 

Physical evidence:
The front seat passenger was in possession of the following items:
- Item A: One zip lock bag containing suspected marijuana, recovered from the front center console.
     Weight: 4.7 grams 

Attachments: 
The above CDS was processed according to MSP policy and procedure utilizing the following documents which are attached:
     One (1) Maryland State Police Property Record P-343443 (MSP FORM 63).
     One (1) Maryland State Police Chain of Custody (MSP FORM 67).
     One (1) Civil Citation (0Z46648427).

Narrative: 
    On January 30, 2023 at approximately 0342 hours, I was sitting stationary on the southbound side of MD Rt. 235 (Three Notch Rd) near St. Johns Rd. I observed a black Nissan Altima, bearing Maryland registration 4BV3127, traveling southbound in lane 1, to be traveling faster than the posted speed limit of 55MPH. I activated my Pro Laser unit (#200-2200-00) and obtained a target speed of 72MPH. I positioned my patrol car behind the vehicle and activated my emergency equipment to conduct a traffic stop on southbound MD Rt 235, south of St. John's Rd. I did not lose sight of the vehicle.   Trooper Eckrich #7350 and Trooper Pettyjohn #7329 arrived to assist. 

    I made a driver's side approach and observed no one seated in the driver's seat. The front seat passenger identified herself as Ahmaya Alexis Ann Cutchember (B/F DOB: 06/15/2003), who advised that the driver jumped out of the vehicle while it was still in motion, after I activated my emergency equipment. Cutchember initially advised that she did not know the name of the driver, and that they were heading home. The two back seat passengers identified themselves as Natasha Arianna Melissa Young (B/F DOB: 06/06/2003) and Isiaih Alexander Woodland (B/M DOB: 09/06/2004.) Later, all advised that the registered owner, Christopher Shayne Campbell (B/M DOB: 01/01/1995), was the driver who bailed out of the vehicle.  I detected the odor of marijuana emitting from the vehicle. All three advised that they do smoke in the vehicle. I conducted a probable cause search of the vehicle and located a small bag containing suspected marijuana (Item A) in the front center console. No further contraband was located during the search. Cutchember claimed the suspected marijuana. I also located Campbell's United States Passport, student ID, and cellphone in the vehicle during the search. 

    I identified the above listed CDS through my training, knowledge, and experience as a Maryland State Trooper.

    I cited Cutchember for Possession of Marijuana: Less than 10 Grams on a Civil Citation (#0Z46648427.) Cutchember is currently on a valid Maryland permit only.

    On January 30, 2023, at approximately 0630 hours, I applied for charges on Campbell for fleeing and eluding as well as hindering. At approximately 1025 hours, Corporal Jackson #5561 received a phone call from Shanasha Jordan, Campbell's sister, advising that Campbell had reported his vehicle as stolen to Officer Ryan Jensrud 7085 #1534 of the Washington DC MPD at approximately 0412 hours on January 30, 2023. Jordan advised Cpl. Jackson that she had just picked Campbell up from the police department. I received a copy of the reporting officer's incident report, which advised that Campbell flagged down the reporting officer on the side of the street and advised that his friend drove off in his vehicle. Campbell further advised the reporting officer that he dropped his friend off at the bar, and waited for her in the back seat. Campbell advised that his friend returned and drove the vehicle, and they began to argue. Campbell advised that the friend stopped the vehicle and they got into a physical altercation. These events occurred in Washington D.C.
     Campbell completed a Maryland State Police Written Statement (MSP 076) at the Leonardtown Barrack at approximately 1534 hours on 01/30/2023. In the statement, Campbell advised that on 01/29/2023 at approximately 2000 hours, he dropped three passengers off at Bar Code, a bar in Washington DC. Campbell advised that he sat in the backseat and waited for them to return. Campbell advised that the three passengers returned at approximately 0200 hours on 01/30/2023, and Woodland sat in the driver's seat and drove the vehicle without Campbell's permission. Campbell stated that Woodland threatened to call his brothers to "shoot up the car." Campbell advised that Woodland stopped the vehicle and began to physically assault him. Campbell advised during the altercation, Cutchember reached into his pocket and took his cellphone and car key fob. Campbell advised that the three drove off in the vehicle, leaving Campbell on the side of the street. Campbell advised that he walked for approximately a quarter of a mile, where he flagged down a patrol officer to report the incident. Both documents are attached to this report. 

        On January 31, 2023, I emailed the reporting officer to speak to him further about the incident. I also emailed the police department's Internal Affairs to receive bodycam footage from when the incident was reported.

        Upon re-watching my in-car camera footage, I did not observe anyone exiting the vehicle prior to the vehicle stopping or when the vehicle came to a complete stop. 

        The vehicle was towed by Southern Maryland Towing and stored. The three occupants were picked up by a licensed driver.

        I request this case remain open pending further investigation. 

    All events occurred in St. Mary's County, Maryland.

This incident was captured on body-worn camera.

On February 6, 2023, I responded to 23200 Leonard Hall Dr., Leonardtown, St. Mary's County, Maryland 20650 to follow up with Christopher Shayne Campbell on the traffic stop involving his vehicle. 

Campbell advised around 0800 hours on 01/29/2023, Ahmaya Cutchember texted Campbell and told him that she wanted to go to breakfast, and she wanted to drive Campbell's vehicle. Campbell advised that he gave her permission to drive his vehicle at the time. Campbell advised that Ahmaya wanted to pick up their friend, Isiaih Woodland. Campbell advised that he told Ahmaya that he did not want Isiaih in the vehicle, because he doesn't like when Isiaih and Ahmaya are together. Campbell advised that Ahmaya picked up Isiaih anyways. Campbell advised that Ahmaya was still driving the vehicle, and picked up one of her cousins, who Campbell did not know, and they went to a hotel in Washington D.C. Campbell advised they all exited the vehicle to go inside the hotel. Campbell advised that upon returning to the vehicle, he sat in the back seat with Ahmaya's cousin. Campbell advised that Ahmaya was in the passengers seat and Woodland was driving the vehicle to a bar in Washington D.C. Campbell advised when they arrived at the bar, the three passengers exited and Campbell remained in the vehicle for approximately 2-3 hours. Campbell advised when the three returned, Isiaih sat in the driver's seat, Ahmaya sat in the passenger's seat, and her cousin sat in the back with Campbell. Campbell advised that all three were intoxicated. Campbell advised that he told Isiaih several times to stop the vehicle so Campbell can drive, due to Isiaih running red lights, and exceeding the posted speed limit. Campbell advised that Isiaih eventually pulled over and exited the vehicle, and kicked the back door. Campbell advised that he grabbed Isiaih and slammed him on the ground to keep Isiaih from hitting him. Campbell advised that he released Isiaih when he was telling Ahmaya that he couldn't breathe. Campbell advised that Isiaih came at him again, and Campbell took him to the ground again. Campbell advised while this was happening, Ahmaya was grabbing his jacket, and this is when Campbell believes Ahmaya took his key fob and cellphone from his pocket. Campbell advised that he released Isiaih again, which is when Isiaih and Ahmaya got into the vehicle and left Campbell. Campbell advised that he believes Isiaih drove the vehicle when leaving, however he did not observe it. All events occurred in Washington D.C.

Ahmaya has been stopped in Campbell's vehicle prior, with Campbell in the passengers seat during her most recent traffic stop. Campbell stated that Ahmaya has no reason to believe that she can regularly drive the vehicle with his permission, and Isiaih did not have permission to drive the vehicle on the night of the incident. 

Since the initial stop, I have reviewed my body worn camera and in-car camera footage. Upon review, I did not see anyone flee from the vehicle. I also could not see in the video which passenger may have moved from the driver's seat. THe rest of the case was handled in Washington D.C.

At this time, I request this case to be closed.
